<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0979B227ECC5FEDE254F4B4C" blockId="45.[151,1437,150,501]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227ECC5FEDE21AB4B35" bold="true" box="[199,416,258,284]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Short description:</emphasis>
Male with large sail-like dorsal fin having 12–16 fin rays, dorsal-fin origin in front of vertical of pelvic-fin origin. The Mexican Molly 
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0979B227EE83FEFB23464B68" authorityName="Valenciennes" authorityYear="1846" box="[641,845,295,321]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" genus="Poecilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sphenops">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227EE83FEFB23464B68" box="[641,845,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Poecilia sphenops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, another introduced fish to the Arabian Peninsula has a dorsal fin with usually 9 rays, not forming a sail and dorsal-fin origin behind vertical of pelvic-fin origin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0979B227ECC5FEB2259D4BA0" blockId="45.[151,1437,150,501]" box="[199,1430,366,393]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227ECC5FEB221CD4BA1" bold="true" box="[199,454,366,392]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">General distribution:</emphasis>
North America: southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3454DCD0979B227EF17FEB323684BA0" box="[789,867,367,393]" name="United States of America" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
to Tuxpan, 
<collectingCountry id="F3454DCD0979B227EFEAFEB3244A4BA0" box="[1000,1089,367,393]" name="Mexico" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Mexico</collectingCountry>
; introduced widely elsewhere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3485ED60979B227ECC5FE4E22CA4BDC" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0979B227ECC5FE4E22CA4BDC" blockId="45.[151,1437,150,501]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227ECC5FE4E21D34B85" bold="true" box="[199,472,402,428]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
Distribution in 
<collectingCountry id="F3454DCD0979B227ED86FE4E21D84B85" box="[388,467,402,428]" name="Oman" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Oman</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
Al Bahayes and Al-Amarat (Al Amirat), 
<collectingRegion id="4996C3BF0979B227EFB9FE4F24A84B84" box="[955,1187,403,429]" country="Oman" name="Masqat" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Muscat Governorate</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="136911D80979B227E8B7FE4F25004B84" box="[1205,1291,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 53" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1333,1357]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1309]" captionTargetId="figure-28@46.[151,1436,181,1309]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 53. Distribution map of Poecilia latipinna, an established exotic fish of Oman. Pink: Southwestern Arabian Coast, green: Oman Mountains, and yellow: Arabian Interior." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541677" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541677/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Both Wadi Al-Bahayes and Al-Amarat are richly vegetated, with the former being flat brackish water body and the latter is a mountainous area (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC370AC0979B227ED95FE0722BE4BDC" author="Al Jufaili, S. M. &amp; Jawad, L. A." box="[407,693,475,501]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" pagination="4 - 5" refId="ref22316" refString="Al Jufaili, S. M. &amp; Jawad, L. A. (2020) First confirmed record of an established population of Sailfin Molly, Poecilia latipinna (Actinopterygii: Cyprinodontiformes: Poeciliidae), in the freshwater areas of Oman, with description of an imperfect albinism incidence. Fisheries, 23, 4 - 5. https: // doi. org / 10.30825 / 5. ejpau. 195.2020.23.4" type="journal article" year="2020">Al Jufaili &amp; Jawad, 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF2D5DD50979B227EC95F9D820D34C69" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541675" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6541675" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541675/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" startId="45.[151,250,1540,1564]" targetBox="[151,1436,525,1517]" targetPageId="45">
<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0979B227EC95F9D820D34C69" blockId="45.[151,1436,1540,1600]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227EC95F9D8212A4C35" bold="true" box="[151,289,1540,1564]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">FIGURE 52.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0979B227ED2BF9D821EB4C35" baseAuthorityName="Lesueur" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[297,480,1540,1564]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" genus="Poecilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latipinna">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227ED2BF9D821EB4C35" box="[297,480,1540,1564]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Poecilia latipinna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an established exotic fish of Oman; upper) male; lower) female (photos: J.E. Randall, Fish-Base).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C3485ED60979B227ECC5F9B2227D4D81" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BED0D5D0979B227ECC5F9B2240E4D49" blockId="45.[151,1436,1646,1960]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227ECC5F9B221364CA1" bold="true" box="[199,317,1646,1672]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Remarks:</emphasis>
Among the methods of introducing an alien species is the aquarium trade, which proves to be the eminent introduction pathway. Both Wadi Al-Bahayes and Al-Amarat where the fish specimens collected have aquarium shops that deal with freshwater fish species of all sorts. There are two possibilities for the presence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0979B227EC95F90721124CDD" baseAuthorityName="Lesueur" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[151,281,1754,1780]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" genus="Poecilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latipinna">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227EC95F90721124CDD" box="[151,281,1754,1780]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">P. latipinna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the inland waters of 
<collectingCountry id="F3454DCD0979B227EE2AF906227B4CDD" box="[552,624,1754,1780]" name="Oman" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Oman</collectingCountry>
. First, the fish may have been released to any of these two localities by ornamental fish hobbyist. Second, specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5276DE0979B227EEC7F92323434D31" baseAuthorityName="Lesueur" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[709,840,1790,1816]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" genus="Poecilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="latipinna">
<emphasis id="B926D14F0979B227EEC7F92323434D31" box="[709,840,1790,1816]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">P. latipinna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have been mixed with fish specimens brought from neighboring countries in an aim to combat mosquitos that transmit malaria. This introduction was made by the Ministry of Health in 
<collectingCountry id="F3454DCD0979B227ED89F89A21C44D49" box="[395,463,1862,1888]" name="Oman" pageId="45" pageNumber="496">Oman</collectingCountry>
during the early 1990s (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC370AC0979B227EEE3F89A23F24D49" author="Al Jufaili, S. M. &amp; Jawad, L. A." box="[737,1017,1862,1888]" pageId="45" pageNumber="496" pagination="4 - 5" refId="ref22316" refString="Al Jufaili, S. M. &amp; Jawad, L. A. (2020) First confirmed record of an established population of Sailfin Molly, Poecilia latipinna (Actinopterygii: Cyprinodontiformes: Poeciliidae), in the freshwater areas of Oman, with description of an imperfect albinism incidence. Fisheries, 23, 4 - 5. https: // doi. org / 10.30825 / 5. ejpau. 195.2020.23.4" type="journal article" year="2020">Al Jufaili &amp; Jawad 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
